International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP)
Activity Description: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP). The project has two overarching goals: 1) reducing mortality among women or reproductive age, their newborns, and children under 5, and 2)increasing community and health system resiliency. The Recipient will use an integrated approach by focusing on the Minimum Service Package (MSP)2 with an emphasis on reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child health and nutrition (RMNCH+Nutrition) coupled with appropriate wrap-around support services that address life-threatening challenges for communities (e.g. malnutrition, cholera, diarrhea). The project will foster an enabling environment and strengthen the health system by improving policies, strategies, practices, and local ownership.

Activity Name: [Redacted] Provision of Information Management SUpport to Yemen Crisis Response Clusters
Activity Description: The project aims to provide Information Management (IM) support to clusters responding to the Yemen crisis. The project provides IM support and coordination services, including cluster/sector lead agencies, and approximately 130 active organizations encompassing other international agencies and nongovernmental organizations (NGOs). [Redacted] direct support to core coordination mechanisms has contributed to enhancing cross-hub operations as well as better information-sharing amongst clusters by providing IM tools that enable situational awareness and common analysis to guide decision making and inform sectoral and inter-sectoral response planning.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Bureau for Democracy, Conflict and Humanitarian Assistance
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, International Assistance Program, Transition Initiatives
Activity Name: Asia, Europe, and the Middle East (AME) Catch-All
Activity Description: Development Transformations recently received a long-term award from USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives (OTI) to provide rapid assessment capacity, short-term technical assistance, and programmatic and logistical support to inform, manage, and implement OTI-funded activities in the Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East regions. The objective of this new Task Order, part of the USAID Support that Augments Rapid Transitions Indefinite Quantity Contract, is to provide timely and responsive support to initial, emerging, and established OTI country engagements and programs.USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives supports U.S. foreign policy objectives by helping local partners advance peace and democracy in priority countries in crisis. Seizing critical windows of opportunity, OTI works on the ground to provide fast, flexible, short-term assistance targeted at key political transition and stabilization needs. DT looks forward to supporting OTI and its programs throughout Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and the Middle East.

US Sector Name: Pandemic Influenza and Other Emerging Threats (PIOET)
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP)
Activity Description: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP). The project has two overarching goals: 1) reducing mortality among women or reproductive age, their newborns, and children under 5, and 2)increasing community and health system resiliency. The Recipient will use an integrated approach by focusing on the Minimum Service Package (MSP)2 with an emphasis on reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child health and nutrition (RMNCH+Nutrition) coupled with appropriate wrap-around support services that address life-threatening challenges for communities (e.g. malnutrition, cholera, diarrhea). The project will foster an enabling environment and strengthen the health system by improving policies, strategies, practices, and local ownership.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Bureau for Democracy, Conflict and Humanitarian Assistance
International Purpose Name: Civilian peace-building, conflict prevention and resolution
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
Activity Description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Improve Access to Quality Education in Yemen I
Activity Description: The goal of this program is to restore education opportunities for out-of-school children (OOSC) in two northern governorates and one southern governorate of Yemen (Sana'a, Hodeidah and Al Dhale'e, respectively). This program will increase access to safe and quality education through improved service delivery at all levels and will expand equal access to education to meet that meets the needs of crisis-affected children.

Activity Name: Yemen Continuous Learning and Evaluation Program (YCLE)
Activity Description: Yemen Continuous Learning and Evaluation Program (YCLE)

Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP)
Activity Description: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP). The project has two overarching goals: 1) reducing mortality among women or reproductive age, their newborns, and children under 5, and 2)increasing community and health system resiliency. The Recipient will use an integrated approach by focusing on the Minimum Service Package (MSP)2 with an emphasis on reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child health and nutrition (RMNCH+Nutrition) coupled with appropriate wrap-around support services that address life-threatening challenges for communities (e.g. malnutrition, cholera, diarrhea). The project will foster an enabling environment and strengthen the health system by improving policies, strategies, practices, and local ownership.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Improve Access to Quality Education in Yemen II
Activity Description: This program will increase access to safe and quality education through improved service delivery at all levels and will expand equal access to education to meet the needs of crisis-affected children. It will leverage its established relationships and programming in Aden, Amran, and Lahj to create a viable, strengthened pathway for the children to return to school and receive remedial support.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Middle East Economic Growth
Activity Description: The Middle East Economic Growth (MEG) Best Practices activity is a new, buy-in field support mechanism to provide ME Bureau field operating units with knowledge, tools, and best practices to promote economic growth, financial management, and business expansion effectively in the MENA region across a variety of operating contexts and in response to a variety of economic growth needs. MEG will support requests from the ME Bureau field operating units for assessments and diagnostics, program designs and model scopes of work, technical briefs and case studies, and pilot and bridge activities. Knowledge-sharing is a central focus of the mechanism; activities will promote economic growth best practices in policy, processes, and capacity building.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Strengthening Family Planning Services in Yemen Project
Activity Description: The two-year Strengthening Family Planning Services in Yemen project will leverage existing activities to strengthen the quality of and access to FP services in 75 healthcare facilities across 6 Governorates. Strengthening Family Planning Services in Yemen Project in Yemen, will leverage established relationships and programming in the proposed target Governorates of Hodeida, Saada, Hajjah, Amran, Lahj and Sanaa.

International Purpose Name: Basic drinking water supply and basic sanitation
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: WASH APS
Activity Description: This project intends to meet the short-term needs of vulnerable populations in terms of access to adequate water and sanitation systems and awareness/knowledge on hygiene practices, while building institutional/operational capacities of public/private service providers and promoting innovative water-saving methodologies at HH level and sustainable water resources management in agriculture.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP)
Activity Description: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP). The project has two overarching goals: 1) reducing mortality among women or reproductive age, their newborns, and children under 5, and 2)increasing community and health system resiliency. The Recipient will use an integrated approach by focusing on the Minimum Service Package (MSP)2 with an emphasis on reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child health and nutrition (RMNCH+Nutrition) coupled with appropriate wrap-around support services that address life-threatening challenges for communities (e.g. malnutrition, cholera, diarrhea). The project will foster an enabling environment and strengthen the health system by improving policies, strategies, practices, and local ownership.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Asia and Middle East Economic Growth Best Practices (AMEG) Project
Activity Description: The Asia and Middle East Economic Growth Best Practices project (AMEG) supports USAID bureaus and missions in Asia, the Middle East, and North Africa with activities such as assessments, strategic planning, diagnostics, and innovative pilot programs. The project focuses on a variety of key issues around economic growth and job creation: public financial management, trade and customs, access to finance, small and medium enterprise development, workforce development, and sustainable livelihoods, particularly for youth and women.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP)
Activity Description: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP). The project has two overarching goals: 1) reducing mortality among women or reproductive age, their newborns, and children under 5, and 2)increasing community and health system resiliency. The Recipient will use an integrated approach by focusing on the Minimum Service Package (MSP)2 with an emphasis on reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child health and nutrition (RMNCH+Nutrition) coupled with appropriate wrap-around support services that address life-threatening challenges for communities (e.g. malnutrition, cholera, diarrhea). The project will foster an enabling environment and strengthen the health system by improving policies, strategies, practices, and local ownership.

Activity Description: Through the Comprehensive WASH support to conflict-affected populations in Yemen (CWS), the Recipient has developed an innovative program that will support and improve sustainable environmental health conditions of vulnerable communities in Yemen, as a result in improvements in WASH infrastructure and service delivery.

Activity Description: The five-year Gateway to Education activity will address both the immediate needs of in-school and out-of-school children and the long-term issue of rebuilding a functioning education system for the school-aged population. Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP)
Activity Description: Yemen-Health: Strengthening Health And Resilience Project (SHARP). The project has two overarching goals: 1) reducing mortality among women or reproductive age, their newborns, and children under 5, and 2)increasing community and health system resiliency. The Recipient will use an integrated approach by focusing on the Minimum Service Package (MSP)2 with an emphasis on reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child health and nutrition (RMNCH+Nutrition) coupled with appropriate wrap-around support services that address life-threatening challenges for communities (e.g. malnutrition, cholera, diarrhea). The project will foster an enabling environment and strengthen the health system by improving policies, strategies, practices, and local ownership.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Middle East Economic Growth
Activity Description: The Middle East Economic Growth (MEG) Best Practices activity is a new, buy-in field support mechanism to provide ME Bureau field operating units with knowledge, tools, and best practices to promote economic growth, financial management, and business expansion effectively in the MENA region across a variety of operating contexts and in response to a variety of economic growth needs. MEG will support requests from the ME Bureau field operating units for assessments and diagnostics, program designs and model scopes of work, technical briefs and case studies, and pilot and bridge activities. Knowledge-sharing is a central focus of the mechanism; activities will promote economic growth best practices in policy, processes, and capacity building.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Bureau for Democracy, Conflict and Humanitarian Assistance
Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Maternal and Child Health Integrated Project (Y-MCHIP), Phase-II
Activity Description: Yemen has one of the highest maternal and child mortality rates in the world. Its reproductive health challenges can be addressed with proven, preventable, and for the most part affordable, low-tech interventions under the most challenging conditions. USAID/Yemen MCHIP-will strengthen the Ministry of Public Health and Population's (MoPHP) reproductive and child health systems performance and address improving health seeking behavior at both the household and facility levels of health institutions. Y-MCHIP is divided into a field support Phase I which conducted various assessments, including a needs and gap analysis on maternal, nutrition, and child health as well as family planning/reproductive health care services at the household and at both governmental and private facility service levels.

Activity Name: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
Activity Description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Yemen Emergency Crisis Response Project - Education
Activity Description: This USAID supported intervention will make significant impact to ongoing education activities in a very difficult situation across the country. Providing continuous support to bridge critical gaps in the Education Response to the crisis, the activity targets the most vulnerable, affected children with particular focus on areas with IDP children. This project restores access and re-entry to basic education with UNICEF and the Ministry of Education (MoE) through Back-to-School Programs (60,000 students are receiving school bags and basic learning supplies), support to administer year-end exams Grade 9 and 12, a Safer School project (planned for 11 governorates), minor physical rehabilitation of schools (200 schools), self-learning (15,000 students targeted) and psychosocial support.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Middle East Economic Growth
Activity Description: The Middle East Economic Growth (MEG) Best Practices activity is a new, buy-in field support mechanism to provide ME Bureau field operating units with knowledge, tools, and best practices to promote economic growth, financial management, and business expansion effectively in the MENA region across a variety of operating contexts and in response to a variety of economic growth needs. MEG will support requests from the ME Bureau field operating units for assessments and diagnostics, program designs and model scopes of work, technical briefs and case studies, and pilot and bridge activities. Knowledge-sharing is a central focus of the mechanism; activities will promote economic growth best practices in policy, processes, and capacity building.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Bureau for Democracy, Conflict and Humanitarian Assistance
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, International Assistance Program, Transition Initiatives
Activity Name: Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East (AEEME) Regional Short Term Technical Assistance (STTA) Catch-All
Activity Description: In July 2014, Development Transformations received a long-term award from USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives (OTI) to provide technical and operations support for countries throughout the Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East regions. The period of performance for this work is August 2014 to October 2017. The purpose of this three-year contract, funded via the USAID/OTI Support that Augments Rapid Transitions (START) Indefinite Quantity Contract (IQC), is to provide rapid assessment capacity, direct distribution of goods and services, short-term technical assistance, and operational, logistical, and programmatic support to inform, manage, and implement activities in these regions. DT looks forward to continuing its work with USAID/OTI as it helps local partners advance peace and democracy in priority countries in crisis or undergoing political transition.

Activity Description: In July 2014, Development Transformations received a long-term award from USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives (OTI) to provide technical and operations support for countries throughout the Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East regions. The period of performance for this work is August 2014 to October 2017. The purpose of this three-year contract, funded via the USAID/OTI Support that Augments Rapid Transitions (START) Indefinite Quantity Contract (IQC), is to provide rapid assessment capacity, direct distribution of goods and services, short-term technical assistance, and operational, logistical, and programmatic support to inform, manage, and implement activities in these regions. DT looks forward to continuing its work with USAID/OTI as it helps local partners advance peace and democracy in priority countries in crisis or undergoing political transition.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Maternal and Child Health Integrated Project (Y-MCHIP), Phase-II
Activity Description: Yemen has one of the highest maternal and child mortality rates in the world. Its reproductive health challenges can be addressed with proven, preventable, and for the most part affordable, low-tech interventions under the most challenging conditions. USAID/Yemen MCHIP-will strengthen the Ministry of Public Health and Population's (MoPHP) reproductive and child health systems performance and address improving health seeking behavior at both the household and facility levels of health institutions. Y-MCHIP is divided into a field support Phase I which conducted various assessments, including a needs and gap analysis on maternal, nutrition, and child health as well as family planning/reproductive health care services at the household and at both governmental and private facility service levels.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Emergency Crisis Response Project - Education
Activity Description: This USAID supported intervention will make significant impact to ongoing education activities in a very difficult situation across the country. Providing continuous support to bridge critical gaps in the Education Response to the crisis, the activity targets the most vulnerable, affected children with particular focus on areas with IDP children. This project restores access and re-entry to basic education with UNICEF and the Ministry of Education (MoE) through Back-to-School Programs (60,000 students are receiving school bags and basic learning supplies), support to administer year-end exams Grade 9 and 12, a Safer School project (planned for 11 governorates), minor physical rehabilitation of schools (200 schools), self-learning (15,000 students targeted) and psychosocial support.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Emergency Crisis Response Project - Livelihoods
Activity Description: The 24-month Emergency Crisis Response Project aims to mitigate the impact of the current crisis on local households and communities and assist their recovery from the bottom-up using local systems, capacities and institutions to progressively resume and scale-up service delivery. The project will achieve specific results in increasing sustainable employment and livelihoods opportunities, including health and education; and reviving the agricultural sector through support to key value chains. The Project's Theory of Change assumes that if income-generation and livelihoods opportunities are increased for youth and women (including IDPs), Yemeni households and communities will be able to better cope with the impact of the current crisis and be strong drivers of the resilience-building and recovery efforts. The project will target about 9,572 direct beneficiaries.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Public Works Project
Activity Description: The establishment of the Public Works Projects came as a pressing necessity to mitigate the adverse effects of the Economical, Financial and Administrative Reform Program as a model for efficient delivery of basic infrastructure services within well defined and transparent procedures.  PWP Main Objectives:  Creating job opportunities for skilled and unskilled laborers; Providing infrastructure service projects for the poor and deprived communities;  Improving the economical and environmental conditions of the poor; Developing the local contracting and consulting Industry; Enhancing community participation in the development process.

International Purpose Name: Decentralisation and support to subnational government
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Emergency Crisis Response Project - Livelihoods
Activity Description: The 24-month Emergency Crisis Response Project aims to mitigate the impact of the current crisis on local households and communities and assist their recovery from the bottom-up using local systems, capacities and institutions to progressively resume and scale-up service delivery. The project will achieve specific results in increasing sustainable employment and livelihoods opportunities, including health and education; and reviving the agricultural sector through support to key value chains. The Project's Theory of Change assumes that if income-generation and livelihoods opportunities are increased for youth and women (including IDPs), Yemeni households and communities will be able to better cope with the impact of the current crisis and be strong drivers of the resilience-building and recovery efforts. The project will target about 9,572 direct beneficiaries.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Emergency Crisis Response Project - Education
Activity Description: This USAID supported intervention will make significant impact to ongoing education activities in a very difficult situation across the country. Providing continuous support to bridge critical gaps in the Education Response to the crisis, the activity targets the most vulnerable, affected children with particular focus on areas with IDP children. This project restores access and re-entry to basic education with UNICEF and the Ministry of Education (MoE) through Back-to-School Programs (60,000 students are receiving school bags and basic learning supplies), support to administer year-end exams Grade 9 and 12, a Safer School project (planned for 11 governorates), minor physical rehabilitation of schools (200 schools), self-learning (15,000 students targeted) and psychosocial support.

Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring and Evaluation Project II
Activity Description: YMEP2 will monitor the progress of activities, report outcomes, and evaluate effectiveness of programs vis-a-vis development objectives specified in USAID's Country Development Cooperation Strategy (CDCS) for 2014 -2016 and the subsequent strategy. The scope of services to be performed includes overall program performance analyses, project and activity-level performance monitoring and evaluation services, as well as prerequisite planning, systems development and management, training and orientation, and outreach and communications support services. Services are to be provided in collaboration with USAID/Yemen program implementing partners. The objective is to advance collaboration and learning that will impact future programming as much as drive necessary adaptations in response to a highly complex and often restrictive operating environment.

Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, International Assistance Program, Transition Initiatives
Activity Name: Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East (AEEME) Regional Short Term Technical Assistance (STTA) Catch-All
Activity Description: In July 2014, Development Transformations received a long-term award from USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives (OTI) to provide technical and operations support for countries throughout the Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East regions. The period of performance for this work is August 2014 to October 2017. The purpose of this three-year contract, funded via the USAID/OTI Support that Augments Rapid Transitions (START) Indefinite Quantity Contract (IQC), is to provide rapid assessment capacity, direct distribution of goods and services, short-term technical assistance, and operational, logistical, and programmatic support to inform, manage, and implement activities in these regions. DT looks forward to continuing its work with USAID/OTI as it helps local partners advance peace and democracy in priority countries in crisis or undergoing political transition.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Bureau for Democracy, Conflict and Humanitarian Assistance
International Purpose Name: Civilian peace-building, conflict prevention and resolution
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
Activity Description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring and Evaluation Project II
Activity Description: YMEP2 will monitor the progress of activities, report outcomes, and evaluate effectiveness of programs vis-a-vis development objectives specified in USAID's Country Development Cooperation Strategy (CDCS) for 2014 -2016 and the subsequent strategy. The scope of services to be performed includes overall program performance analyses, project and activity-level performance monitoring and evaluation services, as well as prerequisite planning, systems development and management, training and orientation, and outreach and communications support services. Services are to be provided in collaboration with USAID/Yemen program implementing partners. The objective is to advance collaboration and learning that will impact future programming as much as drive necessary adaptations in response to a highly complex and often restrictive operating environment.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring and Evaluation Project II
Activity Description: YMEP2 will monitor the progress of activities, report outcomes, and evaluate effectiveness of programs vis-a-vis development objectives specified in USAID's Country Development Cooperation Strategy (CDCS) for 2014 -2016 and the subsequent strategy. The scope of services to be performed includes overall program performance analyses, project and activity-level performance monitoring and evaluation services, as well as prerequisite planning, systems development and management, training and orientation, and outreach and communications support services. Services are to be provided in collaboration with USAID/Yemen program implementing partners. The objective is to advance collaboration and learning that will impact future programming as much as drive necessary adaptations in response to a highly complex and often restrictive operating environment.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Maternal and Child Health Integrated Project (Y-MCHIP), Phase-II
Activity Description: Yemen has one of the highest maternal and child mortality rates in the world. Its reproductive health challenges can be addressed with proven, preventable, and for the most part affordable, low-tech interventions under the most challenging conditions. USAID/Yemen MCHIP-will strengthen the Ministry of Public Health and Population's (MoPHP) reproductive and child health systems performance and address improving health seeking behavior at both the household and facility levels of health institutions. Y-MCHIP is divided into a field support Phase I which conducted various assessments, including a needs and gap analysis on maternal, nutrition, and child health as well as family planning/reproductive health care services at the household and at both governmental and private facility service levels.

Activity Description: The Science &Technology Policy Fellowships provide opportunities to outstanding scientists and engineers from a broad range of disciplines, backgrounds, and career stages to learn first-hand about policymaking and implementation while contributing their knowledge and analytical skills to policymakers. The Fellowship experience builds the capacity of scientists and engineers to effectively inform individuals and organizations that influence and determine public policies, regulations and funding decisions. Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen-Maternal and Child Health Integrated Project (Y-MCHIP), Phase-II
Activity Description: Yemen has one of the highest maternal and child mortality rates in the world. Its reproductive health challenges can be addressed with proven, preventable, and for the most part affordable, low-tech interventions under the most challenging conditions. USAID/Yemen MCHIP-will strengthen the Ministry of Public Health and Population's (MoPHP) reproductive and child health systems performance and address improving health seeking behavior at both the household and facility levels of health institutions. Y-MCHIP is divided into a field support Phase I which conducted various assessments, including a needs and gap analysis on maternal, nutrition, and child health as well as family planning/reproductive health care services at the household and at both governmental and private facility service levels.

Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, International Assistance Program, Transition Initiatives
Activity Name: Asia, Europe, and the Middle East (AME) Catch-All
Activity Description: Development Transformations recently received a long-term award from USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives (OTI) to provide rapid assessment capacity, short-term technical assistance, and programmatic and logistical support to inform, manage, and implement OTI-funded activities in the Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and Middle East regions. The objective of this new Task Order, part of the USAID Support that Augments Rapid Transitions Indefinite Quantity Contract, is to provide timely and responsive support to initial, emerging, and established OTI country engagements and programs.USAIDs Office of Transition Initiatives supports U.S. foreign policy objectives by helping local partners advance peace and democracy in priority countries in crisis. Seizing critical windows of opportunity, OTI works on the ground to provide fast, flexible, short-term assistance targeted at key political transition and stabilization needs. DT looks forward to supporting OTI and its programs throughout Asia, Europe and Eurasia, and the Middle East.

Implementing Partner Sub-category ID: Church and Faith Based - United States
Implementing Partner Name: Adventist Development and Relief Agency International
International Purpose Name: Civilian peace-building, conflict prevention and resolution
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
Activity Description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Private Sector Productivity
Activity Description: Improve the capacity of businesses to integrate into domestic and international markets through increases in productivity and improvements in corporate governance and the development and application of modern technology and marketing practices. Enhance the capacity of businesses and business associations in terms of their corporate governance capabilities and their application of best practices and technologies to achieve increased production and marketing of products and services. It includes adoption of efficient production processes, improved labor productivity, environmentally-sound management of natural resources and the development of accounting and management systems that can help the company and industry group implement business, labor, product and process standards that enhance business competitiveness. Business capacity development programs may include activities that help men- and women-owned firms and associations respond to these international markets and create regional alliances.

Activity Name: Asia and Middle East Economic Growth Best Practices (AMEG) Project
Activity Description: The Asia and Middle East Economic Growth Best Practices project (AMEG) supports USAID bureaus and missions in Asia, the Middle East, and North Africa with activities such as assessments, strategic planning, diagnostics, and innovative pilot programs. The project focuses on a variety of key issues around economic growth and job creation: public financial management, trade and customs, access to finance, small and medium enterprise development, workforce development, and sustainable livelihoods, particularly for youth and women.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Department of State, Global Health Programs
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Bureau for Democracy, Conflict and Humanitarian Assistance
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, International Disaster Assistance
Activity Name: Capacity Building, Preparedness, and Planning
Activity Description: Improve the ability of the USG, host countries and other partners to prepare for and mitigate the effects of disasters, including both natural disasters and complex emergencies, taking into account the differences in men and womens freedom of movement and access to information. Activities under this component include any efforts to enhance the capacities of the USG (in Washington and in the field), humanitarian assistance providers, national host-country authorities, and local communities to engage in disaster reduction and response activities. Activities consist of standardized and coordinated assessments, monitoring, information sharing, data and situational analysis, joint planning; enhancement of coping mechanisms, including the capacity to address adaptation to constantly changing situations on the ground including climate variability and climate change.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Managing Sub-agency or Bureau Name: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
US Sector Name: Pandemic Influenza and Other Emerging Threats (PIOET)
Funding Account Name: Centers for Disease Control, Disease Control, Research, and Training
Funding Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Activity Name: CDC: Measles & Rubella Initiative
Activity Description: The Measles & Rubella Initiative is a global partnership committed to ensuring no child dies from measles or is born with congenital rubella syndrome. Founded originally as the Measles Initiative in 2001, its led by the American Red Cross, the United Nations Foundation, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, UNICEF and the World Health Organization. Since 2001, the Initiative has supported 80 countries to deliver more than 1 billion doses of measles vaccine, helped to raise measles vaccination coverage to 85 percent globally, and reduced measles deaths by 74 percent. Through the Initiative, CDC provides technical assistance to host governments to help plan, implement, and evaluate immunization programs, including operations research, and provides funds to purchase bundled measles vaccine for mass vaccination campaigns.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Implementing Partner Name: International Business and Technical Consultants Inc.
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Yemen Monitoring & Evaluation Project (YMEP)
Activity Description: IBTCI is implementing a Mission-wide M&E program to provide continued, on-the-ground performance monitoring, verification and evaluation of the impact, output and outcome results and environmental compliance of all USAID-funded programs. The goal of the USAID strategy is to increase Yemens stability through targeted interventions in highly vulnerable areas. To accomplish this, the USAID/Yemen Missions strategy employs short and medium term development interventions to impact stability. YMEP is fundamental to this strategy as it will test the hypothesis that the development needs of underserved communities are causally related to improving political and social stability. Stabilization is the process of making a country or territory less likely to descend into, remain in, or return to a state of dysfunction and/or political volatility.

Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Private Sector Productivity
Activity Description: Improve the capacity of businesses to integrate into domestic and international markets through increases in productivity and improvements in corporate governance and the development and application of modern technology and marketing practices. Enhance the capacity of businesses and business associations in terms of their corporate governance capabilities and their application of best practices and technologies to achieve increased production and marketing of products and services. It includes adoption of efficient production processes, improved labor productivity, environmentally-sound management of natural resources and the development of accounting and management systems that can help the company and industry group implement business, labor, product and process standards that enhance business competitiveness. Business capacity development programs may include activities that help men- and women-owned firms and associations respond to these international markets and create regional alliances.

International Purpose Name: Civilian peace-building, conflict prevention and resolution
Funding Account Name: Agency for International Development, Development Assistance
Activity Name: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
Activity Description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Policy Dialogue and Implementation Project (POI) - Health Policy Initiative IQC Task Order 1
Activity Description: The purpose of this task order is to exercise global leadership and provide field level programming in policy development and implementation. The assistance provided under this procurement is expected to improve the enabling environment for health, making it possible for men and women around the world to obtain and use the information and services they need for better health, especially in the areas of family planning/reproductive health (FPIRH), HIV / AIDS, and maternal health (MH). This Task Order will serve as the primary mechanism to support core RHIFP and HIV I AIDS activities in policy dialogue and formulation. The contractor will undertake core-funded global leadership activities including development of indicators to measure overall project progress and impact; development of computer models and other tools and use of new technologies; development work to address health equity issues in policy advocacy, formulation, and implementation; development work to broaden the policy process to include participation by the poor; development of sustainable approaches to build institutional capacities to manage policy change; development work on multi-sector engagement and leadership; and coordination with other donors, particularly other USG and UN agencies.

Implementing Partner Sub-category ID: Universities and Research Institutes - United States
International Sector Name: Maternal and Child Health, Family Planning
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Sustainable Development of Dry lands (IALC)
Activity Description: This project addressed directly the twin threats of desertification and drought which represent enormous obstacles to sustainable development and that threaten the lives and livelihoods of millions of men, women and children in Asia and the Middle East with unbridled competition for resources, and could increase the likelihood of armed conflicts. Three interdependent objectives were implemented: (1) Improve wise use and re-use of water, treated wastewater and soil resources at the farm, community and regional levels; (2) Support human and institutional capacity development in arid lands agricultural development and conservation by partnering with educational and other institutions of host country nations, (3) Apply appropriate technology, especially information technology, to support sustainable arid lands development.

International Purpose Name: Civilian peace-building, conflict prevention and resolution
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Peace and Reconciliation Processes
Activity Description: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

Funding Account Name: International Affairs Technical Assistance
Activity Name: Technical Assistance for Banking and Financial Services
Activity Description: Technical Assistance Programs provide long-term, resident advisors or short-term, intermittent advisors. Banking and Financial Services Program advisors support counterpart government institutions to promote strong financial sectors in which institutions are well-regulated, stable, accessible, serve as efficient intermediaries between savers and investors, and are resistant to criminal activity. Banking and Financial Services Program advisors support ministries of finance, central banks, banking regulation and supervision departments, deposit insurance agencies, and other banking sector entities in an effort to assist in the creation of viable, market-oriented banking systems that serve as both sound repositories of funds and efficient providers of capital to productive sectors of the economy.

Funding Account Name: Department of State, Educational and Cultural Exchange Programs,
Activity Name: Restoration of Dar Al-Diyafa in Zabid
Activity Description: To support the restoration of the Dar Al-Diyafa, the Old Court Building, in the World Heritage city of Zabid. Zabid was the capital of Yemen from the 13th to the 15th century and was prominent for many centuries for its Islamic University. The Old Court Building was built in 1914 by Osta Salem Shami, one of the most famous master builders of Yemen. Like most of Zabid, this building requires urgent repairs and stabilization.

Activity Name: Global Measles Immunization Initiatives through UNICEF.
Activity Description: Global Measles Immunization Initiatives through UNICEF. The Measles Initiative, launched in 2001, is a partnership committed to reducing measles deaths    globally, with the goal of cutting measles deaths by 90 percent by 2010 compared with estimates from 2000.    Through the Initiative, CDC provides technical assistance to host governments to help plan, implement, and    evaluate immunization programs, including operations research, and provides funds to purchase bundled measles    vaccine for mass vaccination campaigns.

Funding Account Name: Department of State, Educational and Cultural Exchange Programs,
Activity Name: Preservation of South Arabian Texts Inscribed on Wood
Activity Description: To support the conservation, cataloging, and publishing of texts that are currently inscribed on more than 500 sticks. Many are in poor condition and are deteriorating. Over 3000 sticks are inscribed with Sabaean texts dating from 800 B.C. to 400 A.D. The sticks report the activities of ordinary individuals, and are unique sources of information about social conditions in Yemen before the advent of Islam.

Implementing Partner Sub-category ID: Universities and Research Institutes - United States
Funding Account Name: Economic Support Fund
Activity Name: Sustainable Development of Dry lands (IALC)
Activity Description: This project addressed directly the twin threats of desertification and drought which represent enormous obstacles to sustainable development and that threaten the lives and livelihoods of millions of men, women and children in Asia and the Middle East with unbridled competition for resources, and could increase the likelihood of armed conflicts. Three interdependent objectives were implemented: (1) Improve wise use and re-use of water, treated wastewater and soil resources at the farm, community and regional levels; (2) Support human and institutional capacity development in arid lands agricultural development and conservation by partnering with educational and other institutions of host country nations, (3) Apply appropriate technology, especially information technology, to support sustainable arid lands development.

Activity Name: Restoration of the Ishah Mudbrick Palace in Tarim
Activity Description: The palaces in this region represent an irreplaceable architectural heritage from the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Over the last 30 years, the mud-brick buildings have been neglected and in some cases abandoned, falling into a state of severe disrepair. This project will focus on emergency repairs to the Ishah Palace located in Tarim.

Funding Account Name: Department of State, National Endowment for Democracy
Activity Name: National Endowment for Democracy Grant
Activity Description: National Endowment for Democracy Grant. The National Endowment for Democracy (NED) is a private, nonprofit foundation dedicated to the growth and strengthening of democratic institutions around the world. Each year, NED makes more than 2,000 grants to support the projects of non-governmental groups abroad who are working for democratic goals in more than 100 countries.
